METHOD:PUBLISH
UID:scalingpuppet@cfgmgmtcamp.eu
SUMMARY:Scaling and monitoring your puppetserver for thousands of clients - including all pitfalls!
ORGANIZER:Tim Meusel
CATEGORIES:talk
DTSTAMP:20181228T000000Z
TZID:Europe-Brussels
DTSTART:20190204T140000
DTEND:20190204T145500
DESCRIPTION;ALTREP="https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/scalingpuppet/":Scaling and monitoring your puppetserver for thousands of clients - including all pitfalls!
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:@"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN""><HTML><BODY><p>Throwing hardware on your Puppetserver to scale it vertically works up to a certain level.<br />
But how do you proceed once you reach the limit?<br />
How do you distribute your agents over several Puppetservers evenly, but without hardcoded assignments?<br />
How do you handle the massively increased load on your Foreman and PuppetDB intances,
after the Puppetserver isn&rsquo;t the bottleneck anymore?<br />
And how the heck can this all be monitored?</p>

<p>I would like to show you a walkthrough from a small environment with a single physical server for Puppetserver/Foreman/PostgreSQL
and a handful of agents that got scaled up to several thousand agents.<br />
This also includes probably all common pitfalls that you can find yourself in on this journey!</p>
</BODY></HTML>";
URL:https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/scalingpuppet/
LOCATION:3.puppet
CLASS:PUBLIC
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
METHOD:PUBLISH
UID:solid@cfgmgmtcamp.eu
SUMMARY:Applying SOLID principles to Infrastructure as Code
ORGANIZER:Bram Vogelaar
CATEGORIES:talk
DTSTAMP:20181227T000000Z
TZID:Europe-Brussels
DTSTART:20190204T173000
DTEND:20190204T182500
DESCRIPTION;ALTREP="https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/solid/":Applying SOLID principles to Infrastructure as Code
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:@"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN""><HTML><BODY><p>S.O.L.I.D is an acronym for the first five object-oriented design(OOD) principles by Robert C. Martin, in the early 2000s.</p>

<p>These principles, when combined together, make it easy for a programmer to develop software that are easy to maintain and extend.<br />
They also make it easy for developers to avoid code smells, easily re-factor code, and are also a part of the agile or adaptive software development.</p>

<p>This talk discusses our options how we can model puppet code while applying the SOLID principles.<br />
As the puppet DSL is not a object oriented language we will also address the limitations of the design pattern,
which we ll have to solve using the convention over configuration design pattern.</p>
</BODY></HTML>";
URL:https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/solid/
LOCATION:0.daula
CLASS:PUBLIC
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
