UID:keynote0@cfgmgmtcamp.eu
SUMMARY:Observability for emerging infra: what got you here won't get you there
ORGANIZER:Charity Majors
CATEGORIES:keynote
DTSTAMP:20181226T000000Z
TZID:Europe-Brussels
DTSTART:20190204T093000
DTEND:20190204T102500
DESCRIPTION;ALTREP="https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/keynote0/":Observability for emerging infra: what got you here won't get you there
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:@"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN""><HTML><BODY><p>Distributed systems, microservices, containers and schedulers, polyglot persistence &hellip;<br />
modern infrastructure is ever more fluid and dynamic, chaotic and transient.<br />
Likewise, individual engineering roles can no longer be broken down neatly into<br />
software engineers (who write the code) and ops engineers (who deploy the code (and buffer the consequences)).<br />
Many teams have already sailed past an event horizon of complexity and found that their old tools and processes no longer work for them.</p>

<p>But why, exactly?<br />
What was wrong with traditional metrics and logs?<br />
Why are they failing to keep pace with modern requirements?<br />
Isn&rsquo;t observability just a marketing term for monitoring? And what on earth can we do about it?</p>

<p>In this talk we&rsquo;ll cover the shortcomings of traditional metrics and logs,
and the technical and cultural differences between monitoring and observability.<br />
We&rsquo;ll also talk about the deep cultural revolution underway from siloed specialties
towards software ownership (in every type of engineering role) &ndash;
and what exactly does that mean when it comes to systems observability? &ndash;
as well as the technical practices and mental shifts that are absolutely required to keep pace with modern infrastructure.</p>
</BODY></HTML>";
URL:https://cfgmgmtcamp.eu/schedule/monday/keynote0/
LOCATION:0.daula
CLASS:PUBLIC
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
